      "tier3": "Solar panels, also known as photovoltaic (PV) panels, work through the photovoltaic effect.  This effect describes the creation of voltage or electric current in a material upon exposure to light.  Solar panels are made of numerous PV cells, typically constructed from silicon.  Silicon is a semiconductor, meaning it can conduct electricity under certain conditions.  Within each cell, there are layers of silicon doped with different impurities (n-type and p-type).  The n-type layer has extra electrons, while the p-type layer has holes (missing electrons).  When sunlight strikes the cell, photons from the sunlight excite electrons in the silicon, causing them to break free from their atoms.  The electric field created by the junction between the n-type and p-type layers directs these freed electrons towards the n-type layer, creating a flow of electrons – an electric current. This current is then collected by metallic contacts on the surface of the cell and channeled out to form usable electricity.  The more cells connected together in a panel, the greater the amount of electricity generated."
